:::summary
Hammurabi (c. 1810–1750 BC) was the sixth king of the First Babylonian Empire and one of the most important rulers of the ancient world. He is best remembered for the *Code of Hammurabi* — one of the earliest and most complete written legal codes in history — which established the principle that a ruler's duty is to bring justice to his people.
:::

